        "symptom": "Fatigue",
        "description": "A general feeling of tiredness or lack of energy can occur due to decreased oxygen supply to body tissues."
      },
      {
        "symptom": "Palpitations",
        "description": "Patients may experience irregular heartbeats or a sensation of the heart racing due to arrhythmias associated with the defect."
      },
      {
        "symptom": "Cyanosis",
        "description": "Bluish discoloration of the skin, lips, or nails can occur when oxygen-rich blood is not adequately delivered to the body, often indicative of more severe cases."
      },
      {
        "symptom": "Swelling",
        "description": "Swelling in the legs, abdomen, or around the eyes may occur due to fluid retention related to heart failure."
      }
    ],
    "treatments": "Treatment for Ebstein's Anomaly varies depending on the severity of symptoms and associated complications. In mild cases, regular monitoring may be sufficient. Medications such as diuretics, beta-blockers, or antiarrhythmic drugs can be used to manage symptoms and improve heart function. In more severe cases, surgical intervention may be necessary. This can include repairing the malformed tricuspid valve, placing a prosthetic valve, or potentially performing a more extensive procedure such as atrial septal defect repair or Fontan procedure. Each treatment plan is tailored to the individual patient's needs and should be determined by a cardiologist experienced in congenital heart defects."
